[3] United Nations General Assembly
Date: Tue 21 Sep 2021
Source: CIDRAP (Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy) [edited]
https://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2021/09/un-general-assembly-opener-highlights-pandemic-covid-19-vaccine-gaps


On the 1st day of high-level discussion at the United Nations General Assembly, leaders of Brazil and the United States were among the first to address the gathering, underscoring underlying tensions about COVID-19 measures but also drawing needed attention to vaccine gaps.

Brazil President Jair Bolsonaro, the 1st leader to speak, touched on the pandemic in his speech, but other elements of his presence drew attention to his defiance over tough COVID-19 measures, according to the Washington Post (https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2021/09/21/brazil-bolsonaro-vaccine-un-general-assembly/).

Bolsonaro reportedly isn't fully vaccinated, and United Nations rules specify that those in the General Assembly hall must be vaccinated under an "honor system." Brazil's leader has said he doesn't need to be vaccinated because he has immunity following a previous infection.

During his speech, he said his administration supports vaccination efforts, but not vaccine passports or mandates. He also said COVID-19 restrictions have hurt country economies, according to Al Jazeera (https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/9/21/world-leaders-united-nations-general-assembly).

Meanwhile, US President Joe Biden in his address to leaders said collective action and political will is needed to bring the pandemic to an end. He said a new mechanism is needed to fund global health security against future threats (https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefing-room/speeches-remarks/2021/09/21/remarks-by-president-biden-before-the-76th-session-of-the-united-nations-general-assembly/). He also alluded to a global COVID-19 virtual summit he is hosting tomorrow [22 Sep 2021], and he hinted that the United States will make additional commitments.

More global headlines
---------------------
- In Australia, violent protests flared in Melbourne for the 2nd day in a row, with protesters airing frustrations about lockdowns and pushing back against a plan to require construction workers to be vaccinated, according to the Washington Post (https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2021/09/21/australia-melbourne-vaccine-protests-construction-lockdown/).
- China reported 42 more cases today [21 Sep 2021] in Fujian province outbreaks, including 36 from Xiamen, according to the country's National Health Commission (http://en.nhc.gov.cn/2021-09/21/c_84642.htm).
- The global total today [21 Sep 2021] topped 229 million and is at 229 400 528 cases, along with 4 705 370 deaths, according to the Johns Hopkins online dashboard (https://coronavirus.jhu.edu/).

[Byline: Lisa Schnirring]

